## Structure (matches the 13 sections in the findings)

### Intro (question-driven; before §1)
- Hook: the rating that best describes a finished season forecasts the next worst. PER ~<< f("panel.PER.describe_median_pct") >>% describe vs ~<< f("panel.PER.forecast_median_pct") >>% forecast in the median season, across << f("panel.n_seasons") >> tested.
- Three questions: (1) do the systems agree? (2) what does each uniquely capture? (3) how should they be combined?
- Settled up front: no single best system; agree at the top, diverge below; value is top-heavy (gap #1→#10 >> #10→#50).
- Testbed 2025-26; << f("cov.n_systems") >> box-score systems + RAPM/RAPM+prior recomputed; other impact + human rankings surveyed only. Two panels span << f("panel.n_seasons") >> seasons back to << f("panel.first_season") >>.

### § 1. The landscape of player rating
- Box-score (recomputed, present): Game Score, PER, Win Shares, WS/48, BPM, OBPM, DBPM, VORP.
- Impact metrics (surveyed): RAPTOR, EPM, LEBRON, DARKO, DRIP, ESPN RPM. RAPM backbone + box-score prior; noise/regularization.
- Human rankings (surveyed, not included): MVP votes, All-NBA, media top-100.
- Practitioner trust (external, cited in resources bibliography): HoopsHype survey of 29 execs, DARKO top at 8 votes; Dunks & Threes retrodiction order EPM > RPM > RAPTOR > BPM 2.0.

### § 2. Do the systems agree?
- Spearman matrix. Tight: PER-Game Score << f("corr.GAME_SCORE_PER") >>, BPM-VORP << f("corr.BPM_VORP") >>. Moderate: PER-WS << f("corr.PER_WS") >>, WS-WS/48 << f("corr.WS_WS48") >>. Loose: PER-BPM << f("corr.PER_BPM") >>, Game Score-BPM << f("corr.GAME_SCORE_BPM") >>.
- Player-level divergence even where overall correlation is high: WS favors efficient bigs (<< f("loves.WS.1.name") >>, << f("loves.WS.2.name") >>); PER favors high-usage scorers (<< f("loves.PER.1.name") >>, << f("loves.PER.3.name") >>).
- RAPM sits apart: agrees with box scores at << f("rapm.box_corr_mean") >>; bare 2025-26 puts reserve << f("rapm.top.1.name") >> at #<< f("rapm.top1_consensus_rank") >> in consensus. Fixed RAPM+prior agrees with consensus << f("rapm_my.consensus_corr") >> (up from << f("rapm.consensus_corr") >>, ~double) but very top still catches low-minute noise (<< f("rapm_my.top.1.name") >>); RAPM+prior (combined only) feeds the consensus.
- Chart: rank-agreement heatmap.

### § 3. What the field has learned about evaluating these metrics
- Two community tests: retrodiction (1st-half → 2nd-half outcomes) and team-wins prediction; both reward a RAPM backbone + calibrated box-score prior. Academic caveat: complex metrics don't reliably beat simple ones as inputs to downstream salary/wins models.
- Direct describe test (held-out teams, 2025-26): PER best, ~<< f("retro.top.cv_r2_pct") >>% of team point-diff, above the plus/minus metrics.
- Forecast test (prior-season ratings predict this season): order flips, PER ~<< f("nextretro.PER.r2_pct") >>%, best forecaster << f("nextretro.top.name") >> ~<< f("nextretro.top.r2_pct") >>%. Coverage ~<< f("nextretro.coverage_pct") >>%.
- Multi-season panel (<< f("panel.n_seasons") >> seasons / << f("panel.n_pairs") >> handoffs back to << f("panel.first_season") >>): PER describes ~<< f("panel.PER.describe_median_pct") >>%, forecasts ~<< f("panel.PER.forecast_median_pct") >>% (median handoff); best forecaster << f("panel.forecast_top.name") >> ~<< f("panel.forecast_top.mean_pct") >>%; BPM beats PER forecasting << f("panel.bpm_beats_per_pairs") >>/<< f("panel.n_cmp_pairs") >> handoffs.
- Impact-era panel (<< f("ipanel.n_seasons") >> seasons from << f("ipanel.first_season") >>, box scores vs RAPM): bare RAPM forecasts << f("ipanel.RAPM.forecast_rank") >>/<< f("ipanel.n_systems") >> (~<< f("ipanel.RAPM.forecast_mean_pct") >>%, describe ~<< f("ipanel.RAPM.describe_mean_pct") >>% but mechanical), RAPM+prior tops the forecast (<< f("ipanel.RAPM_MY.forecast_rank") >>/<< f("ipanel.n_systems") >>, ~<< f("ipanel.RAPM_MY.forecast_mean_pct") >>%) above every box score, while bare RAPM sits mid-pack; forecast leader << f("ipanel.forecast_top.name") >>.
- Stability (year-over-year): Game Score retains << f("stability.GAME_SCORE.retention_pct") >>% of its top << f("stability.top_n") >>, PER << f("stability.PER.retention_pct") >>% (chance ~<< f("stability.chance_pct") >>%); steadiest << f("stability.most_stable.name") >> << f("stability.most_stable.corr") >>, jumpiest << f("stability.least_stable.name") >> << f("stability.least_stable.corr") >>; << f("stability.n_pairs") >> pairs. Stickiness cuts against forecasting (PER sticky but weak forecaster; plus/minus metrics jumpier but better forecasters).
- Charts: retrodiction, next-season retrodiction, panel describe-vs-forecast, impact panel, rating stability.

### § 4. What each system uniquely sees
- Overlap R² (own kin held out; high = redundant): most redundant PER << f("overlap.PER.r2") >>, BPM << f("overlap.BPM.r2") >>; least redundant WS/48 << f("overlap.WS48.r2") >>, bare RAPM << f("overlap.RAPM.r2") >>, WS << f("overlap.WS.r2") >>; DBPM slid to mid << f("overlap.DBPM.r2") >> after the RAPM fix. Caveat: BPM/VORP validated vs BBR; RAPM now carries real signal, so its low overlap reads as genuine independence.
- System-outliers chart: who each system rates above/below consensus.

### § 5. The two uber ratings
- Consensus (average normalized score). Top 5: << f("consensus.top.1.name") >> << f("consensus.top.1.z") >>, << f("consensus.top.2.name") >> << f("consensus.top.2.z") >>, << f("consensus.top.3.name") >> << f("consensus.top.3.z") >>, << f("consensus.top.4.name") >> << f("consensus.top.4.z") >>, << f("consensus.top.5.name") >> << f("consensus.top.5.z") >>.
- Wins-predictive (weighted by team-wins prediction). Top: << f("wins_pred.top.1.name") >> << f("wins_pred.top.1.z") >>, << f("wins_pred.top.2.name") >> << f("wins_pred.top.2.z") >>.
- Consensus vs. wins-predictive Spearman << f("cmp.spearman") >>. Top riser << f("cmp.higher.1.name") >> +<< f("cmp.higher.1.diff") >>; top faller << f("cmp.lower.1.name") >> << f("cmp.lower.1.diff") >>. Wins-predictive lifts stars on winning teams, discounts production on losing teams.

### § 6. Stars matter more than rank implies (distribution section)
- Rate metrics spread evenly: PER top-5% share << f("dist.PER.top5pct", "{:.1f}%") >>. Cumulative top-heavy: WS top-5% << f("dist.WS.top5pct", "{:.1f}%") >>, VORP << f("dist.VORP.top5pct", "{:.1f}%") >>.
- Power-law steepness (alpha): PER << f("powerlaw.PER.alpha") >> (shallowest); the cumulative metrics and uber ratings cluster higher (VORP << f("powerlaw.VORP.alpha") >>, Consensus << f("powerlaw.CONSENSUS.alpha") >>, Wins-Pred << f("powerlaw.WINS_PRED.alpha") >>), up to the noisy plus/minus halves. Two groups by R² fit: straight-line power laws (incl. WS, BPM) vs. benders (per-possession metrics; VORP is the bending exception, concentrated but just short of the line).
- RAPM full distribution (<< f("rapm_shape.n_seasons") >> seasons, << f("rapm_shape.n") >> player-seasons, << f("rapm_shape.frac_neg") >>% below 0) is a symmetric bell, not a power law (lacks the one-sided tail); VORP leans right (the precondition a power law's shape needs), though its own top-50 curve bends just short.
- Gini kept only as a cross-check; it misleads on 0-centered metrics (Consensus Gini << f("dist.CONSENSUS.gini") >> > WS << f("dist.WS.gini") >>, an artifact, not real top-heaviness).
- Charts: all-systems distributions, distribution shape, power-law small multiples, power-law fits, gini, rank-value curves, ordinal-vs-value gap.

