### § 8. Who rose and fell in the playoffs
- Box-score rate metrics recomputed on playoff games only (impact metrics can't: a playoff run is too few games; only the recompute family splits by season type, see inventory). << f("playoff.n_qualified") >> players ≥ << f("playoff.min_floor") >> playoff minutes; change measured against that peer group (strips the leaguewide playoff dip).
- Two reliability guards: shift shrunk toward zero by playoff minutes (half weight at << f("playoff.shrink_minutes") >>) so a short sample can't top the list; game-level bootstrap range (re-draw games << f("playoff.bootstrap_b") >>x), a shift is "clear" when its range excludes zero; only << f("playoff.n_clear") >> of << f("playoff.n_qualified") >> clear it.
- Risers: << f("playoff.riser.1.name") >>, << f("playoff.riser.2.name") >>, << f("playoff.riser.3.name") >>. Fallers: << f("playoff.faller.1.name") >>, << f("playoff.faller.2.name") >>, << f("playoff.faller.3.name") >>, incl. regular-season consensus #1 << f("playoff.consensus1.name") >>. One postseason, not proof.

### § 9. What changed from 2024-25 to 2025-26
- Snapshot read of the most recent full-season pair (<< f("cmp2.n_both") >> players qualified in both). Consensus order agrees << f("cmp2.consensus_corr") >> year-over-year: top stable (<< f("cmp2.top_b.1.name") >>, << f("cmp2.top_b.2.name") >> lead both; only << f("cmp2.held_top5") >> of top 5 carry over), middle churns.
- Biggest mover up << f("cmp2.riser.1.name") >> (<< f("cmp2.riser.1.delta") >>), down << f("cmp2.faller.1.name") >> (<< f("cmp2.faller.1.delta") >>); one-year swings, not signal. What did NOT change: box-score agreement << f("cmp2.agree_a") >> → << f("cmp2.agree_b") >>, disagreement is structural. Chart: season comparison (consensus movers).

### § 10. Summary
- Re-answers the three questions: agree at the top / each captures less uniquely than it looks (heavy overlap) / two combined ratings agreeing at << f("cmp.spearman") >>.
- Through-line: value is top-heavy. Caveat: single-season cross-system comparison is a snapshot; the describe-vs-forecast and stability panels (<< f("panel.n_seasons") >> seasons) are the firmer results.

### § 11. A note on the recomputed formulas
- PER cleanest (mean ~15, Jokić low 30s). WS/BPM/VORP are approximations; absolute values differ from BBR.
- VORP inflation for high-steal defenders: VORP rates << f("loves.VORP.1.name") >> further above consensus than any player (per-100 denominator uses player-possessions not team-possessions). Also Ausar Thompson, Dunn.

### § 12. Limitations
- Single-season cross-system testbed; only the describe-vs-forecast and stability panels reach across << f("panel.n_seasons") >> seasons.
- RAPM now computed from play-by-play (2025-26 back to << f("ipanel.first_season") >>, << f("cov.rapm_n_players") >> players in 2025-26): bare = noisy, no prior; RAPM+prior = 3 pooled seasons + BPM prior (consensus corr << f("rapm_my.consensus_corr") >>); over the << f("ipanel.n_seasons") >>-season panel RAPM+prior tops the forecast (above every box score), bare RAPM does not. No tracking data, so can't match EPM/LEBRON.
- Tracking/team-internal blind spot (Second Spectrum, Synergy, franchise models).
- Playoff small-sample limit for RAPM-based metrics.

### § 13. What a Bayesian lens would add
- Uncertainty ranges: single-number metrics hide a ~2-3 pts/100 band; apparent 8th-vs-12th disputes often within it.
- Playoff vs. regular season: update the full-season prior with playoff lineup data; posterior barely shifts on 6 games, more on a Finals run.
- Better consensus weighting: estimate system weights from multi-season retrodiction.

